North Korea Says ‘Don’t Think’ of Unilateral Disarmament Without Confidence
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the continuation of sanctions was exacerbating distrust of the United States and that there was no way for the country to unilaterally dispense with its nuclear weapons in these circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly of the world body that North Korea had taken "significant measures of goodwill" last year, such as the discontinuation of nuclear and missile tests, the dismantling of the nuclear testing center and the commitment to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and technologies.
“However, we do not see any corresponding response from the US,” he said.
“Without confidence in the U.S., there will be no confidence in our national security and under such circumstances there is no way we can proceed to our disarmament first.”
Although Ri has recycled already known North Korean complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “phased” approach to denuclearization, under which North Korea would be rewarded as it took gradual steps, his statements appear to be significant to the extent that they do not intrinsically reject previous unilateral denuclearization.
Ri cited a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first ever summit between a U.S. president in office and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, where Kim pledged to work toward “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump offered security guarantees to North Korea.
North Korea has sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States says Pyongyang must first abandon its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease tough international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'denuclearization first' and increases the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve its goal coercively, opposing even the 'declaration of the end of the war'," Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an impossible dream of people who know nothing about us.
However, the problem is that the extension of sanctions is aggravating our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for the second summit between Kim and Trump that had been referred to by the U.S. leader at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: "If the party concerned in this matter were South Korea and not the US, denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have reached this impasse."
Still, the tone of Ri’s speech was drastically different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that directing North Korea’s rockets toward U.S. territory was inevitable after “Mr. Bad President” Trump called Kim the “rocket man” on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year had threatened to “completely destroy” North Korea, lauded Kim for his courage in taking steps toward disarmament, but said there was still much to be done and that sanctions would have to continue until North Korea denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump said he didn’t have a calendar for it, saying “it doesn’t matter if it takes two years, three years, or five months.”
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps it has taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday, “The implementation of Security Council sanctions must continue vigorously until denuclearization is complete, final and verifiable.”
The Security Council unanimously tightened sanctions on North Korea since 2006 in an attempt to stifle funding for North Korea's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but the last visit did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July saying progress had been made, though North Korea later denounced him for "making gangster demands.
In a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile facility and also a nuclear complex if the United States “take appropriate action.”
Pompeo said Kim had told him that the "corresponding measures" they were looking for were Trump's security guarantees in Singapore, as well as initiatives to normalize relations with Washington.
