"In reality, the fact that an untimely political decision from Washington or Beijing could result in an economic crisis in both countries is far more dangerous than observers could ever have anticipated," said Abigail Grace, an associate researcher at the Center for New American Security, a think tank.
Foreign Minister Says Syria Is Prepared for Refugees’ Return
Syria says it is prepared for the voluntary return of refugees and calls for help to rebuild a country devastated by more than seven long years of war.
In his speech to the UN General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said the country’s conditions are improving.
“Today, the situation on the ground is more stable and secure thanks to progress in the fight against terrorism,” he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate the areas destroyed by the terrorists to restore normalcy.
There are now all the conditions for the voluntary return of refugees to the country who have left due to terrorism and unilateral economic measures that have affected their daily lives and livelihoods.
The United Nations estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since the start of the war in 2011.
Another six million people who have remained in the country need humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian regime would be happy to receive aid for the reconstruction of the devastated country.
However, he stressed that he would not accept conditional assistance or help from the countries that sponsored the revolt.
Europe wins Ryder Cup in Paris
The European team beats the U.S. and wins the 2018 Ryder Cup with a final score of 16.5 to 10.5 at Le Golf National on the outskirts of Paris, France.
The U.S. has now accumulated six consecutive defeats on European soil since winning the Ryder Cup in Europe in 1993.
Europe once again crowned itself victorious after the team of Danish captain Thomas Bjorn reached the 14.5 points they needed to beat the United States.
American star Phil Mickelson, who proved to be in serious trouble for almost the entire tournament, threw the starting tee into the water in hole 16, par 3, giving victory to Francesco Molinari.
Italian golfer Molinari shone in all his rounds, becoming 1 of 4 players to get 5-0-0 since the current format of the tournament began in 1979.
The American Jordan Spieth lost 5&4 to the worst-ranked player in the European team, Thorbjorn Olesen of Denmark.
The world’s highest-ranked player, Dustin Johnson, lost 2–1 to England’s Ian Poulter in what may have been his last Ryder Cup appearance.
A veteran of eight Ryder Cups, Spaniard Sergio Garcia became the most awarded European of all tournaments with 25.5 career points.
“It’s not my habit to cry, but today I couldn’t contain myself.
It's been a tough year.
I can't help but thank Thomas for choosing me and believing in me.
I'm so glad we won the cup.
It was all a team effort and I’m happy to have been able to help,” said an emotional Garcia after Europe’s victory.
He gives the floor to his compatriot Jon Rham, who defeated U.S. golf legend Tiger Woods by 2&1 in singles on Sunday.
“It’s impossible to describe the pride I feel for defeating Tiger Woods. I grew up watching him play,” Rahm, 23, said.
Woods has lost all four games in France and now has a 13-21-3 record in the Ryder Cup.
Unusual statistical values of one of the greatest players of all time with 14 great titles won and only beaten by Jack Nicklaus.
With the exception of Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas and Tony Finau who had a high-calibre performance throughout the tournament, the rest of the U.S. national team struggled to get to the fairway.
Captain Jim Furyk spoke after his team's disappointing performance. "I'm proud of them. They fought.
This morning, we managed to put some fear in Europe.
Let's fight.
My congratulations to Thomas.
He's a great captain.
All 12 players were excellent.
